doc.ContractDescription: M31 (THE ANDROMEDA GALAXY; SB) AND M33 (THE TRIANGULUM GALAXY; SC) ARE UNIQUE IN THAT THEY ARE THE ONLY CLASSICAL SPIRAL GALAXIES IN THE LOCAL GROUP BESIDES THE MILKY WAY (MW). THEIR NEARBY DISTANCES (~780 AND ~840 KPC RESPECTIVELY ) ALLOW FOR THE MOST DETAILED STUDY OF THE STAR FORMING REGIONS IN TYPICAL SPIRAL GALAXIES. WE PROPOSE A PANCHROMATIC SURVEY OF THE STAR FORMATION REGIONS OF M31 AND M33 TO STUDY THE YOUNG STELLAR POPULATIONS AND DUST EXTINCTION PROPERTIES OF BOTH OF THESE NEARBY SPIRALS. OTHER WELL-STUDIED NEARBY SPIRALS (E.G., M51) ARE SIGNIFICANTLY MORE DISTANT AND DO NOT PROVIDE FOR THE LEVEL OF DETAIL PROVIDED BY M31 AND M33. M31 AND M33 HAVE BEEN THE FOCUS OF NUMEROUS OBSERVING CAMPAIGNS OVER A WIDE RANGE OF WAVELENGTHS FROM THE FAR AND NEAR-ULTRAVIOLET, GROUND-BASED OPTICAL, MID- AND FAR-INFRARED, AND SUB-MM. THE KEY NEW INGREDIENTS IN OUR ANALYSIS ARE IMAGES OF M31 AND M33 TAKEN WITH THE SWIFT UV/OPTICAL TELESCOPE (UVOT) IN THREE NEAR- UV FILTERS WHICH PROVIDE IMPORTANT NEAR-UV COLOR INFORMATION AND ALLOW US TO DIRECTLY PROBE THE NATURE OF THE 2175 ANGSTROM BUMP IN THE DUST EXTINCTION PROPERTIES OF THESE NEARBY SPIRALS. WE WILL COMBINE THESE NUV IMAGES WITH MULTIWAVELENGTH ARCHIVAL FUV (FROM GALEX), GROUND-BASED OPTICAL, MID-IR (SPITZER), FAR-IR AND SUB-MM (SPITZER AND HERSCHEL) DATA TO DERIVE THE SPECTRAL ENERGY DISTRIBUTIONS (SEDS) OF STAR FORMING REGIONS IN M31 AND M33 FROM 1400 ANGSTROMS TO 500 MICRONS. THESE MEASUREMENTS WILL ALLOW US TO MAP THE THE STAR FORMATION HISTORIES AND INTERSTELLAR DUST PROPERTIES OF M31 AND M33 IN UNPRECEDENTED DETAIL. OUR PROPOSED PROJECT IS HIGHLY RELEVANT TO THE GOALS OF THE ASTROPHYSICS DATA ANALYSIS PROGRAM BECAUSE IT USES PUBLICLY AVAILABLE DATA FROM MULTIPLE NASA MISSIONS INCLUDING GALEX, SWIFT, SPITZER AND HERSCHEL TO INVESTIGATE THE RECENT STAR FORMATION HISTORY AND DUST EXTINCTION PROPERTIES OF THE ONLY TWO SPIRAL GALAXIES IN THE LOCAL GROUP BEYOND OUR OWN MILKY WAY. THESE PROJECTS ADDRESS ADAP RESEARCH AREAS #2, 6, AND 7. WE WILL MAKE OUR MULTIWAVELENGTH SPECTRAL ENERGY DISTRIBUTIONS OF STAR-FORMING REGIONS IN M31 AND M33 AVAILABLE TO THE ASTRONOMICAL COMMUNITY.
